SIMPLE: proclaim
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Proclaim
<hw>Pro*claim"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Proclaimed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Proclaiming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>proclamen</ets>, L. <ets>proclamare</ets>; <ets>pro</ets> before,
forward + <ets>clamare</ets> to call or cry out: cf. F.
<ets>proclamer</ets>. See <er>Claim</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make known by public announcement; to give wide
publicity to; to publish abroad; to promulgate; to declare; <as>as, to
<ex>proclaim</ex> war or peace</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>proclaim</qex> liberty to the captives.</q> <rj><qau>Isa.
lxi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the apparel oft <qex>proclaims</qex> the man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throughout the host <qex>proclaim</qex>⟦br⟧
A solemn council forthwith to be held.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To outlaw by public proclamation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I heard myself <qex>proclaimed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To publish; promulgate; declare; announce. See
<er>Announce</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proclaimer</ent>⟦br⟧
